1.2 THE CONCEPT OF PROPERTY{\*\bkmkend _Toc171541776}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104734}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229914989} 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par The term property has a variety of uses. In ordinary English, it refers to ownership or title and you usually hear an owner claim that this or that thing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3624146\charrsid11362428 is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \'93his or her property\'94, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3624146\charrsid11362428 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
ometimes, it also refers to the res or the thing over which ownership right is exercised such as a house, a car, a table\'85
. Furthermore, in its broad sense, property means everything that has material or moral value for human beings beginning with their own body, reputation, and freedom to think and act. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3624146\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 However, in its narrower and proper legal sense, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\ul\highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid2827098 property }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid5071993 may be defined as an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid15021672 exclusive right to control, use, transfer\'85
 an object or a thing of economic importance and its fruits, exclude all other persons fro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\highlight7\insrsid5071993\charrsid15021672 m its use and enjoyment and to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid15021672 follow the thing and its fruits in the hands of any person who might have unlawfully taken it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid5071993 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  It is a name for a concept that refers to the rights and obligations, privileges and restrictions that govern the relations of persons with respect to things hav
ing economic or financial value. Hence, accurate legal terminology ought to reserve the use of the word property for designation of rights of persons with respect to things. This is because the use of the concept of property to denote human, civil}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6711648 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  politic
al and family rights would be stretching the concept beyond limits and would cause confusion. Furthermore, it would be inaccurate and narrow to use the concept of property to refer to ownership or title because the legal usage of the term includes other r
ights such as possession, usufruct, use, and servitude. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \highlight3\insrsid2119398\charrsid2827098 The things in relation to which such property rights are exercised are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\ul\highlight3\insrsid2119398\charrsid2827098 objects of property}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \highlight3\insrsid2119398\charrsid2827098  rather than property itself}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 . Hence, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid4343884 the house, or the car, or the table in relation to which an ownership right is exercised is properly called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\highlight7\insrsid2119398\charrsid4343884 an object of the right of ownership.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par Art 40/1/ of the FDRE Constitution which guarantees the right to property provides that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3624146\charrsid11362428 
\par 
\par Property}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  right includes, unless restricted by law for public purposes, the rights to acquire, use, and transfer things/ tangible or intangible/ of financial value.
\par Property rights are rights in-rem in the sense that it creates an obligation, on all other persons, to refrain from any act of interference in the use and enjoyment of a thing one owns or
 possesses. It also entitles a possessor or an owner of a thing to pursue such thing in the hands of any person in to whose possession the thing might have come. It is important to note here that private property is guaranteed and protected not only again
st interference by the government and its agencies but also by individuals and other persons. 
\par In this regard, Art 1206 of the Civil Code provides for the right of an owner to claim and recover the thing owned from any person who, without his consent, posse
sses or holds it and to oppose and repel any act of usurpation. See also Arts 1148 and 1149 of the Civil Code. Compare the remedies available to a creditor to whom performance is not made, Arts 1771-1805 of the same code.  
