\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 According to the positivist theory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 law is nothing but the command of the sovereign, that is, the rules promulgated by government officials for reasons of public policy, protection of individual rights, promote the general welfare, increase social wealth o
r maximize social utility. According to Jeremy Bentham, one of the prominent utilitarian political philosophers, property is the basis of expectation of deriving certain advantages from a thing which we are said to possess, in consequence of the relation 
in which we stand to wards it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
The idea of property consists in an established expectation; in the persuasion of being able to draw such or such an advantage from the thing possessed. Now this expectation, this persuasion, can only be the work of law. I ca
nnot count upon the enjoyment of that which I regarded as mine, except through the promise of the law that guarantees it to me. It is law alone that permits me to forget my natural weaknesses. It is only through the protections of law that I am able to en
close a field, and to give my self up to its cultivation with the sure though distant of harvest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Property and law are b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 orn together and die together. B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
efore laws were made}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 , there was no!}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8193884  property; take a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
way laws, and property ceases. Similarly, E. Jenks argu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5979404 es that private}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 property is a creation of the state and achieved only after a long struggle }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13008050 with the clan. If we consider}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 the essential characteristics of private property, the right to exclude others, the right to charge the thing for a debt, to alienate or leave by will, it is true that the state has provided the machinery by which these rights are enjoyed. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3764058\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 However, this theory is criticized on the ground that the state and private property are the results of the same social and economic forces and w
e can hardly say one is the creation of the other. John Locke argues that the state is the result of a social contract in which the society transferred some of their rights to the state for the purpose of protection their rights including the right to pro
perty.   
