\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Art}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8932256\charrsid11362428 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 1136 of the Civil Code defines an accessory as anything, movable or immovable, which the owner or the possessor / the Amharic version limits to the usufructuary and not other possessors/ of the thing has permanently destined for the use of another thing.
 For instance, if an owner of a car puts a jack permanently for the use of his car the jack shall be considered as the accessory of the car.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8932256\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 A tractor, or a pair of oxen, or a horse put by the owner/possessor of a land for the use of his land is considered
 as accessory. Similarly, a plot of land adjacent to a certain farm that is intended for the use of the farm or a private water well out side a certain farm and which the owner/possessor of the farm has destined for the use of such farm as a source of wat
er is considered as an accessory to the principal thing, the farm.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
