\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 One may define immovable things as things tha
t cannot be moved from one place to another at all or that cannot be moved without being divided in to several parts. From the acontrario reading of Art 1127 of the Civil Code, we may define immovable things as things that cannot move by them selves or be
 moved by man with out losing their individual character.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12482466\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Art 463 of the 1870 Civil Code of Louisiana divided immovable things into three categories: immovables by nature, immovables by destination and immovables by the object/ purpose to which they are ap
plied. Art 462 of the same code defines immovables by nature as things that cannot move by themselves or be moved from one place to another. It further provides that buildings and other constructions shall be considered as immovables by nature regardless 
o
f whether they have their foundations in the soil and the courts have properly classified as immovables things whose foundations rested on blocks or posts. Furthermore, the code does not require unity of ownership as a prerequisite of immobility. Hence, b
uildings and other constructions erected by persons other than the owner of the land are immovables by nature
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12482466\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 However, the definition of immovable things by nature is deleted by the revised civil code of 1978 on the ground that it contradicts the reality s
ince contemporary mechanical advancements make possible the relocation of immense quantities of earth, timber, buildings and various other   kinds of constructions. It appears, therefore, that immovability by nature under the present Louisiana law is a le
g
al fiction based partly on practical considerations and partly on inherent characteristics of things. Hence, in light of contemporary conceptions, the only immovables by nature are tracts of land, i.e., portions of the surface of the earth individualized 
by boundaries.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7807440\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
The 1978 revision made no changes in the classification of buildings. Hence, buildings that belong to the owner of the land/ ground are component parts of the land and are immovables. When the owner of the land/ground is different from the o
wner of the building, the building is considered as a separate immovable. Thus, under the revised code, as under the 1870 code, buildings are classified as immovables. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12482466\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 However, constructions other than buildings are classified, under the revised code, as
 movables unless they are considered as component parts of a tract of land. To be considered as a component part of a tract of land it must meet two requirements: it must be permanently attached to the ground, and it must belong to the owner of the ground
.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7807440\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The term \lquote land\rquote 
 refers to a space as much as it refers to the material of which that part of the land is made. In its spatial aspect, land is immovable, while in its material aspect it may be removed, at least partially, by removing the soil. A house att
ached to land is an immovable in law, but obviously, it may be moved in fact by demolishing. The nature of an immovable cannot be understood unless we realize that, starting from a physical test, the law has gradually extended the notion. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7807440\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The following are special characters of land that distinguishes it from other properties.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7807440\charrsid11362428 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls4\ilvl1\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Land is more enduring than other properties; hence, future interests in land have definite value.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}It is important for purposes of security because of the fact that land canno
t be moved and it is permanent as opposed to furniture or vehicles that may be easily hidden.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}A risk of destruction of the land, for example, by storm or fire is minimal.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}Land can be subdivided with out necessarily losing its value.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}Land is still very necessary for expansion of industries, large farms and creation of means of transport.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
