\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Since both animus and corpus are necessary for possession, possession is lost when one of the two elements ceases to exist. The isolated continuation of one element does not suffice to maintain it. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5663574\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 However, a possessor shall not be considered
 to have lost his possession by the sole fact that, at a given time, he was not able to exercise physical control in relation to the thing or that he did not intend to hold it in his own name and for his own benefit. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2376771\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Possession is lost only by deliberate
 abandonment or by a physical obstacle that makes it impossible to restitute, at any time the possessor desires, the state of affairs that construed the possession. However, this principle does not apply absolutely and we have to make the following distin
ctions. See Art 1142 of the Civil Code.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5663574\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Under French law possession of movable things is lost as soon as they have ceased to be under the power or control of the possessor. Possession of wild
 animals is lost as soon as they have acquired their freedom. Possession of tamed animas such as bees and pigeons is lost when they cease to return habitually to their hives or dovecotes, or when they lose their animus revertendi, i.e., \lquote 
their intention/habit to return\rquote .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9982682\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Possession of immovable things can be preserved solo-animo, i.e., it is not lost just because the possessor has voluntarily abstained, for a time, from material or physical acts of possession or has been incapable to exercise them because 
he was too far away, or because of the nature of the immovable, or because of some temporary obstacle. However, abnormally long intervals between acts of possession, taking in to account the nature of the thing, may be considered as a tacit renunciation. 
Compare Art 1142 of the Civil Code.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195713\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Furthermore, possession is not necessarily lost just because a third person has occupied the immovable. It shall be lost only if he occupies the immovable for a year. /Compare Arts 1142 and 1149 of the C
ivil Code/.  If the former possessor lets this period elapse with out any act of enjoyment or any claim for return of possession, whether he did or did not know of the adverse occupancy, he shall lose his right of possession. This is true even if he manif
ested his intention to continue in possession by acts such as the payment of taxes.
\par 
