{\*\bkmkend _Toc171541811}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104755} AND ELEMNTS OF OWNERSHIP}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\fs24\insrsid2119398 {\*\bkmkend _Toc229915035}
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid13653849 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13653849\charrsid13653849 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Right of ownership is the widest and th
e ultimate property right that may be had in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14302104\charrsid11362428 relation to things or objects. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Ownership may be defined as legal relationship that gives rise to certain rights and obligations between persons in relation to an object. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Ownership is said to be absolute in the sense that the owner may do as he likes with the thing that is his own. The rights of an owner include; 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li1620\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1620\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls8\ilvl1\adjustright\rin0\lin1620\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
The right of use and enjoyment, which includes the right to determine to what type of use the object may be put, to deal with the fruits of the thi
ng as he likes, and even the right to destroy the thing or its fruits. See Arts 1205/1/ and 1270-1271 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}
The right of possession that includes the right to exclude others. Property right is essentially a guarantee of the exclusion of oth
er persons from the use and handling of the thing over which the right is exercised and the right to reclaim it from the hands of another. See Arts 1204, 1148 and 1149 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab} The right to transfer the thing and its fruits for consideration 
or gratuitously which could be intervivos / while the owner is alive / or mortis causa/ up on his death/ and the right to charge them as security (mortgage or pledge). See Arts 1205/2/ and 3049/2/ of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}The right to leave or abandon the thing or its fruits at will. See Art 1189 of the Civil Code.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Some other sources also argue that a right of ownership is composed of the following main elements; 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li540\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin540\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428   - The right to use the object himself (the usus)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428             -The right to collect and use frui
ts - such as crops or rents (the fructus)
\par             -The right to dispose of it and its fruits by alienation by destruction (abandonment) and the right to charge it with pledge or mortgage (the abuses)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Ownership is said to be 'exclusive' because these rights are in principle available only to the owner, and is "perpetual" since these rights are neither extinguished by non-usage nor limited by duration. See Art 1204 of the Civil Code. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
The owner can, at will, use or enjoy his property, dispose it of, perform all the legal transactions to which the thing is susceptible, and to exclude all other persons from participating in the exercise of these rights.
\par    
\par However, an owner may not possess or exercise all the rights set out above and his   rights may be restricted by law or by an agreement he has made with another person.
\par For instance, the law of nuisance limits, in the interest of his neighbors, the owner\rquote s right to use his property as h
e wishes or he may transfer some of his rights to another through a contract of usufruct or hire or lease. See Arts 1215-1227 and 1309-1352 of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The term }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 ownership}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  is a convenient method of denoting, as a unit, the various rights and privi
leges that constitute the content of ownership rather than ownership itself. Hence, a person may transfer some or all of these rights while still retaining ownership over the object. For example, an owner who has leased his house shall retain ownership of
 the house even though he has temporarily lost his right to possess and use the house until the term of the lease expires, which shows that ownership is distinct   from its contents.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  The fact that an owner may cede so many rights and still retain ownershi
p raises difficulties of definition. From this we can consider ownership as the magnetic core which remains when all present rights of enjoyment are removed from it and which attracts to itself the various elements temporarily held by others as they lapse
.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 To understand the concept of ownership comprehensively, let us try to distinguish between:
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li1620\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1620\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls9\ilvl1\adjustright\rin0\lin1620\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Ultimate Ownership- in which other persons hold the rights of present enjoyment temporarily through contracts such as usufruct or lease and the residual magnetic core is left to the owner. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}Complete or Beneficial Ownership- in which the owner enjoys all the rights and privileges emanating from it. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104756}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915036}3.2 RESTRICTIONS ON THE RIGHT OWNERSHIP}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\insrsid13653849 {\*\bkmkend _Toc204104756}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915036}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Tough ownership is said to be absolute and exclusive right a person may have relation to things, it may be made subject to various restrictions. See Art 1204/1/ of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 These restrictions may be based on public interest, for instance the law orders that animals 
affected by or suspected of having contagious diseases be reported and isolated, that they not be sold or offered for sale. Compare Arts 2369 and 2373 of the Civil Code.
\par Sale of miracle remedies may be prohibited, sale of medicines is reserved for pharmacists, and the sale of alcohol, narcotics, guns, tobacco, and matches is regulated.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Under French law historical monuments/ antiquities/ may not be sold, if they are owned by the state. And if individuals own them the state has a right of preemption upon the
ir sale by public auctions. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Similarly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 under Ethiopian law/ Research and Conservation of Cultural Heritages Proclamation No 209/2000/, defines cultural heritage as anything tangible or intangible which is the product of, in pre-history or history times, 
human creativity and labor and that reflects the evolution of nature and which has historical, cultural, scientific and artistic value provides for various restrictions on the right of ownership, exploration, discovery and study things that are classified
 as cultural heritages. For instance, cultural heritages discovered after the 27}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
 of June 2000 may not be privately owned / Art 14/2/ and Art 35/3/ of the proclamation. Individuals who own or possess cultural heritages on the coming in to force this law ar
e required to report their possession to the Cultural Heritages Conservation and Research Authority and get them registered. See Art 17 of the proclamation. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The state may confiscate any privately owned cultural heritages whe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  it believes that they are no
t properly protected, repaired or restored or where they are exposed to damage or decay. See Art 25/1/ of the proclamation. The state can also expropriate, against payment of compensation, objects of historical, artistic or archeological interests where i
t
 finds it necessary to preserve them in a museum. See Art 25/2/. Furthermore, transfer of privately owned cultural heritages is subject to prior notification by both parties to Authority which has a right of preemption, i.e., a priority right to purchase 
the cultural heritage.  However, transfer for commercial purposes and transfer out side the country are not allowed under all circumstances. See Arts 23, 24, and 27 of the proclamation.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13653849\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The owner of a movable may be 
deprived of his property through requisition under conditions specified by law; similarly immovable things may be expropriated, against payment of compensation, where they are needed for public purposes. See Arts 1319/2/ 1460 and 1464 of the Civil Code.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 T
he law may also require that an owner be prohibited completely from exercising certain powers naturally inherent in right of ownership, or allow him to exercise them only under specific conditions. Such restrictions or burdens that result from the law con
s
titute statutory/legal servitudes, if they are established with relation to one estate for the immediate benefit of another estate with a character of a dominant estate. Outside this situation, these servitudes are considered as limitations on the exercis
e right of ownership.   
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Public interest or service includes construction of pre-determined public works such as public health, urbanization, conservation of historical or natural monuments and sites, reforestation and conservation forests. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The restric
tion on the right of ownership may also be based on considerations of mutual interest of neighboring estates. In other words, contiguity of land belonging to different persons creates conflicts if, either or both of them, wish to enjoy their holdings with
out any consideration of possible damages or annoyances caused to the other. Restrictions on the powers which ownership right usually involves can prevent these conflicts. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 A.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx720\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls40\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 It is prohibited to undertake on ones estate works or operations that may materia
lly endanger a neighboring estate for instance, excavations or ditches which may result in damages to buildings or agriculture. See Arts 1210 and 1225 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 B.\tab}The law prohibits owners from causing nuisances to a neighbor by noise, smoke, gase
s odor if it exceeds limits considered tolerable. See Art 1225 "Good neighborly behavior". The neighbor who is the victim of such nuisance may require repair of the damage caused or get an injunction/ a court order requiring suspension of such act/ and pa
yment of compensation. See Art 1226.                                   
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 C.\tab}
The law prohibits an from directing water to another's holding waters other than proceeding from rain or a spring and flowing naturally from higher to lower grounds. For example, wat
er from a well, or a shaft, waste or polluted water from industry, water used for irrigation may not be directed to the neighbors land. See Art 1246 (1) of the Civil Code.      
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 D.\tab}The owner of a building must construct the roof so that rainwater falls in to the public road or on his own land. See Art 1245.

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 E.\tab}
Under French law the owner of a wall or a building, which is not far enough from the neighboring estate is required to permit opening of direct or indirect view or access of light through windows with
 wired glass panes "picture windows" and iron grillwork with opening not larger than 10 cm.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 F.\tab}
The owner/holder of land is required by law to allow access to his land/ holding in some circumstances. Hence, he/she may not prohibit access to his}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 /her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428  land where it is necessary: - 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1620\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1620\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
- To prevent or avoid eminent damage or danger to life or property ( Art. 1217)
\par - To repair of walls or buildings (Art 1218)
\par -To recover lost things or animals (Art 1219)
\par - To install of pipes (Arts 1220, 1252, 1253)
\par - To allow right of way to a neighbor (Arts 1221-1224, 1249(2))
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li360\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104757}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915037}3.3 PROPERTY RIGHTS WITH REGARD TO LAND AND WATER}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\insrsid2119398 {\*\bkmkend _Toc204104757}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915037}
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid13653849 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13653849\charrsid13653849 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11362428 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Though property rights with regard to land and water will be discussed in detail by separate courses, i.e., Land Law and Water Law respectively, the rules governing property rights on land and water are briefly discussed in this section with a view to giv
e a general introduction to students.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Land had been, as any object of property, subject to private ownership and had been governed under the Civil Code prior to 1975 when the Derg, the military and communist regime, enacted laws nationalizing rural and urb
an land and abolished private ownership of land. However, individuals were given a right to use land for farming and construction of residential or business buildings against payment of taxes on income from agricultural activities or land tax.  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 After the
 fall of the Derg in 1991 and the ratification of the FDRE Constitution in 1994, land remained public property, however, private ownership of land has become, once again, one of the most important political, economic and social issues in the country. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14954863\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Und
er Art 40 of the FDRE Constitution land/ both rural and urban/ is declared to be the property of the state of Ethiopia and its peoples. See also Art 4 of the Federal Rural Land Administration Proclamation No 1997. However, the constitution entitles Ethiop
i
an farmers and pastueralists to obtain farmland/ pastureland free of charge and a right of use of such land. It also provides that investors in the agriculture sector may also obtain land in accordance with land use laws to be issued by the regions. The l
and use/ holding rights recognized by the constitution and the federal land administration law shall be implemented and administered by the states/ regions of the federation, which shall issue specific laws for the implementation of these rights. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 In urban
 areas, individuals and investors have the right to obtain land necessary for construction of buildings for residential or commercial purposes in accordance with the land lease law issued by the House of Peoples Representatives and City or Regional govern
ments. See Re-enactment of Urban Lands Lease Proclamation No 272/2002.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16279848\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Regarding property rights in relation to water resources, Arts 1255 and 1447 of the Civil Code provide that waterways (rivers), lakes and underground accumulation of water shall be deem
ed to form part of a public domain, i.e., they can not be privately owned, alienated, or acquired through possession in good faith, occupation. See also Art 1454 and 1455. Furthermore, according to Art 40(3) of FDRE Constitution water resources, which inc
lude both surface and underground water, are common property of the peoples and state of Ethiopia.
