\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
\par Prohibition of assignment or attachment arises from a contract or will where by certain things are 
transferred and where by the transferor prohibits the transferee from assigning or transferring the thing to another person. The producer, maker, seller or owner of such thing may impose these prohibitions. See Art 1426 of the Civil Code.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5053408 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Such provisions 
may freely be made with respect to ordinary movable things (chattels). However, such restrictions will bind only the person who accepts them and hence, it does not create a real right that can be raised against third parties. See Art 1426/2/ of the Civil 
Code.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3035004\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 
Prohibition of the right of attachment or assignment with respect to immovable things is possible only in cases allowed by the law. According to Art 1427, 1428 and 929-936 of the Civil Code, the transferor or assignor of an immovable thing or the tes
tator may prohibit the transferor or the holder in tail from assigning an immovable to another person. He may also stipulate that the thing shall not be attached in the hands of the transferee or the holder in tail. See also Art 2460 of the Civil Code.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5053408\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 In
 German law, one cannot impose restraints upon alienation, permanent or temporary, with real effects. Hence, the transferee will not be affected by such provision even if he has notice of it. In French law, on the other hand, one cannot impose permanent r
estraints with either real or personal obligatory effects. If such provisions are made, they shall not bind the transferee. However, one may impose temporary restraints that will bind the transferee whether he has notice of it or not. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3035004\charrsid11362428 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 The rationale behind
, Roman and German law, not allowing such restrict ions is that the interests of commerce are best served by granting the owner the fullest freedom to dispose of his property and free circulation of goods. French law also accepts this principle, but makes
 an exception for a limited period where a serious interest is involved. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5053408 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid11362428 Ethiopian law also follows the same approach in adopting the restriction and provides under, Art 1416 (1), that such restriction with regard to chattels will have no real effect on t
hird parties, unless they knew of the restriction. It also tries to minimize the negative consequences of the restrictions by limiting the period for which it can be made. In other words, a provision prohibiting assignment or attachment cannot be made for
 indefinite period, following the approach taken by French Law. 
\par On the other hand, such restrictions can be made on immovable things with real effects in cases expressly allowed by the law for the purpose of protection of a serious interests, for instance, keeping an immovable with in a family.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s4\qj \li360\ri0\sl360\slmult1\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11362428 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
